article.headline: Wyoming 49, Washington State 47
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- The Cardiac Cowboys pulled out another heart stopper. Dion Sherrell hit two free throws with 14.2 seconds left, and Derek Wabbington iced the game with one final foul shot as Wyoming beat Washington State 49-47 on Wednesday night. It was the fifth consecutive game decided by five or fewer points for the Cowboys (6-3). They've won three of those, including wins against Montana State (71-70) and Creighton (68-64), and losses at Dayton (62-57) and against Kansas State (64-61) in the Wyoming Shootout in Casper. "I think we're getting pretty used to it -- I don't know whether I like that or not," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said. "But on the other side of it, that's what most league games come down to is the last 4 minutes of the game." With 5:03 left, Wyoming led 43-29 and appeared to have the game in hand. But Washington State (5-4) got a pair of 3-pointers from Thomas Kelati, and the Cowboys made it easier on the Cougars by hitting just five of their first 13 free throws, before Sherrell's made it 48-43. Jeff Varem scored a layup with 7.6 seconds left to bring the Cougars within 48-45. Wabbington went to the line with 6.7 seconds left; he missed the first free throw, but hit the second to put the game away. "Going into shooting all of my free throws, I was just going long or short," Wabbington said. "I was one for two each time I went to the line -- I always made the first one and missed the second one." Varem had an uncontested dunk with 1.3 seconds left, but there wasn't time for the Cougars to score again. After back-to-back losses to Dayton and Kansas State, Wabbington said the Cowboys' wins against Creighton and Washington State have given them confidence that they can win close games. "We'd like to beat them by more than that, but as the game gets down to the crunch I feel like everyone's more relaxed," Wabbington said. "It's preparing us for the end of the season." Jay Straight led Wyoming with 13 points, all in the first half. Justin Williams had 10 rebounds. Kelati led Washington State with 16 points. The Cowboys at first seemed stumped by Washington State's aggressive defense, falling behind 10-4 in the opening minutes. But Wyoming found its touch from 3-point range, and a 14-0 run put the Cowboys up for good. Straight tied the game 10-10 on a driving layup with 8:17 left in the first half, then hit a 3-pointer -- the first of the game -- for the go-ahead basket. "They adjusted well," Washington State coach Dick Bennett said. "And as often happens when we go into these droughts, it eventually affects us defensively. They get frustrated and they try to go for a steal or an interception, do something out of character." Meanwhile, the Cougars hit a shooting slump, going scoreless almost 7½ minutes before Kelati hit a 3-pointer to pull the visitors within 18-13. Washington State hit just 6-of-25 from the field in the first half.
